The official opening of the Channel tunnel on May 6 should be the
starting point for recovery in the property market in Kent and
Northeastern France.  Far-sighted prospective buyers looking near
Calais include hauliers wanting to set up a base on the Continent and
Asian entrepreneurs who see an advantage in being close to Belgium.

Growing confidence in the UK market is slowly stimulating interest in
French property, although smaller banks in Calais are none too happy
when Britons seek loans.  Show cash and there are bargains to be had.
Wine Society members can buy wine free from UK taxes.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d39"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT942-11114"
SELECTOR="G"
SUMMARIZER="G">     

The official opening of the Channel tunnel this year promises to help
revitalize the northwest regions of Belgium although the country's
biggest ports will suffer a loss in traffic.  Flanders, the area most
likely to benefit, has suffered rapid increases in unemployment.  Two
main areas for development are: firstly, increasing traffic as holiday
makers and freight carriers head towards the tunnel opening in Calais
and, secondly, tourism.  West Flanders is home to some of the
best-known World War 1 battlefields and large, open green spaces.  The
biggest advantage is the close cooperation between national and
federal authorities with French and UK counterparts.</SUM>
